1
00:01:13,840 --> 00:01:15,170
Let's go sit over there.

2
00:01:15,360 --> 00:01:16,560
The view is nice.

3
00:01:29,880 --> 00:01:30,200
Yeah.

4
00:01:30,200 --> 00:01:32,759
Yaoyao, what do you want to drink? I'll order.

5
00:01:33,440 --> 00:01:34,560
I'll have the usual.

6
00:01:34,560 --> 00:01:36,020
See what he wants to drink.

7
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:38,840
Old man, coffee or tea?

8
00:01:39,160 --> 00:01:39,960
Coffee.

9
00:01:40,640 --> 00:01:41,479
Coffee.

10
00:01:41,479 --> 00:01:42,960
Shouldn't it be tea?

11
00:01:43,320 --> 00:01:45,400
I didn't expect you to be so trendy.

12
00:01:45,680 --> 00:01:46,680
Do you want sugar?

13
00:01:46,759 --> 00:01:47,560
Black coffee.

14
00:01:48,400 --> 00:01:50,800
Where he's from is the origin of coffee.

15
00:01:51,160 --> 00:01:53,620
He's probably been used to it for a long time.

16
00:01:54,520 --> 00:01:55,680
So no sugar.

17
00:01:55,800 --> 00:01:56,680
Hot or iced?

18
00:01:56,680 --> 00:01:57,479
Iced.

19
00:01:58,200 --> 00:01:59,080
I'll go order.

20
00:02:06,480 --> 00:02:08,400
How have you been these past few days?

21
00:02:08,400 --> 00:02:10,320
As a witness to history,

22
00:02:10,320 --> 00:02:11,180
how do you feel?

23
00:02:12,400 --> 00:02:13,240
How do I feel?

24
00:02:15,080 --> 00:02:16,880
I can barely even think about it.

25
00:02:17,480 --> 00:02:18,810
You're quite humorous.

26
00:02:19,320 --> 00:02:20,360
It's not humor.

27
00:02:20,840 --> 00:02:22,900
I really don't dare to think about it.

28
00:02:27,200 --> 00:02:28,040
Lin Yaozu.

29
00:02:28,760 --> 00:02:30,320
What made you and your companions

30
00:02:30,320 --> 00:02:32,640
firmly choose to return to China to help?

31
00:02:35,280 --> 00:02:38,760
I mean, besides patriotism and love for your country,

32
00:02:39,480 --> 00:02:41,120
are there any other reasons?

33
00:02:41,800 --> 00:02:45,130
That made you and your companions risk your lives to return?

34
00:02:52,320 --> 00:02:53,760
Lin Yaozu, come help!

35
00:03:01,040 --> 00:03:01,440
Thank you.

36
00:03:01,440 --> 00:03:02,300
Yaoyao, yours.

37
00:03:12,240 --> 00:03:13,480
How is it?

38
00:03:13,480 --> 00:03:14,360
Not used to it?

39
00:03:15,440 --> 00:03:16,520
It's been a while.

40
00:03:16,760 --> 00:03:17,960
It's going to my head.

41
00:03:18,040 --> 00:03:19,720
Who told you to order black coffee?

42
00:03:19,720 --> 00:03:22,120
You even learned the phrase 'going to my head'.

43
00:03:22,120 --> 00:03:23,380
Do you want some sugar?

44
00:03:24,760 --> 00:03:25,560
No need.

45
00:03:27,840 --> 00:03:28,700
It was justice.

46
00:03:30,360 --> 00:03:31,400
Justice.

47
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:36,060
This cup of bitter coffee brings out a sense of justice.

48
00:03:36,360 --> 00:03:39,160
I believe everyone has a sense of justice.

49
00:03:39,680 --> 00:03:41,410
You mean fighting for justice.

50
00:03:42,120 --> 00:03:42,920
Yes.

51
00:03:43,079 --> 00:03:44,160
Like you said,

52
00:03:44,240 --> 00:03:45,500
fighting for justice.

53
00:03:46,280 --> 00:03:48,520
If we returned to fight for our country,

54
00:03:48,880 --> 00:03:51,880
it's because we are connected by blood to this nation.

55
00:03:52,640 --> 00:03:55,320
But among the Nanqiao mechanics back then,

56
00:03:55,320 --> 00:03:56,800
there weren't just Chinese.

57
00:03:56,800 --> 00:04:00,160
There were also friends from other Southeast Asian countries and regions.

58
00:04:00,160 --> 00:04:01,120
Tell me about it.

59
00:04:02,520 --> 00:04:03,320
Wait.

60
00:04:04,200 --> 00:04:05,520
I need to record this.

61
00:04:11,880 --> 00:04:12,600
Start.

62
00:04:16,320 --> 00:04:18,320
It was 1939.

63
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:02,060
It's settled then.

64
00:05:02,280 --> 00:05:03,200
Are you ready?

65
00:05:06,840 --> 00:05:07,640
Hello, David.

66
00:05:08,760 --> 00:05:10,240
Yaozu, Hanwen.

67
00:05:11,040 --> 00:05:12,200
I want to join you.

68
00:05:12,600 --> 00:05:13,560
Join us?

69
00:05:15,200 --> 00:05:16,760
Join you and go to China.

70
00:05:18,240 --> 00:05:20,640
We are going back to fight a war.

71
00:05:21,280 --> 00:05:22,840
It's to transport supplies.

72
00:05:22,840 --> 00:05:25,080
But the supplies are sent to the frontlines for the war,

73
00:05:25,080 --> 00:05:25,680
right?

74
00:05:25,680 --> 00:05:26,160
Right.

75
00:05:26,160 --> 00:05:27,080
I can drive.

76
00:05:27,240 --> 00:05:29,520
I can go with you to transport supplies.

77
00:05:29,720 --> 00:05:32,159
David, this mission isn't that simple.

78
00:05:32,640 --> 00:05:33,440
It might even

79
00:05:34,600 --> 00:05:35,930
even cost you your life.

80
00:05:36,520 --> 00:05:38,680
Our motherland is now under invasion.

81
00:05:38,680 --> 00:05:40,140
We cannot turn a blind eye.

82
00:05:40,280 --> 00:05:42,080
Nor can we sit and wait for death.

83
00:05:42,320 --> 00:05:43,120
So,

84
00:05:44,320 --> 00:05:46,180
you don't have to do the same as us.

85
00:05:46,640 --> 00:05:49,080
Just stay here and go on with your life.

86
00:05:50,520 --> 00:05:51,320
Look,

87
00:05:51,520 --> 00:05:54,380
the whole city is raising funds to save the country.

88
00:05:54,800 --> 00:05:57,330
All Chinese are donating money and supplies.

89
00:05:57,800 --> 00:06:00,560
We are best friends and brothers.

90
00:06:00,960 --> 00:06:02,690
So I want to go to China with you.

91
00:06:04,080 --> 00:06:05,920
But if you go back with us,

92
00:06:05,920 --> 00:06:07,050
what's in it for you?

93
00:06:09,200 --> 00:06:11,200
Since childhood, we have read the books of sages.

94
00:06:11,200 --> 00:06:13,720
A true man should ordain conscience for Heaven and Earth,

95
00:06:13,720 --> 00:06:15,280
secure life and fortune for the people,

96
00:06:15,280 --> 00:06:16,560
continue lost teachings for past sages,

97
00:06:16,560 --> 00:06:19,160
and establish peace for all future generations.

98
00:06:19,160 --> 00:06:20,620
You might not necessarily

99
00:06:20,720 --> 00:06:22,180
understand these things.

100
00:06:22,320 --> 00:06:25,360
This is the content of the teachings of Confucius and Mencius.

101
00:06:25,360 --> 00:06:28,440
These are the Four Sentences of Hengqu by Mr. Zhang Zai.

102
00:06:29,360 --> 00:06:31,120
My textbooks were all in English.

103
00:06:31,120 --> 00:06:33,440
I haven't heard of what you said.

104
00:06:33,800 --> 00:06:36,080
But my friends around me talk about it all the time.

105
00:06:36,080 --> 00:06:37,010
Talk about what?

106
00:06:37,680 --> 00:06:38,940
Die to achieve virtue.

107
00:06:39,880 --> 00:06:40,680
Okay.

108
00:06:41,080 --> 00:06:42,880
I didn't know you knew idioms.

109
00:06:43,960 --> 00:06:44,840
It's a pity that

110
00:06:45,400 --> 00:06:47,920
this was originally the way of life taught by Confucius and Mencius,

111
00:06:47,920 --> 00:06:51,000
but now it has become a catchphrase in this era of war.

112
00:06:52,400 --> 00:06:53,930
There's a slang in English.

113
00:07:07,520 --> 00:07:09,480
Isn't this just

114
00:07:09,480 --> 00:07:12,400
living and letting live?

115
00:07:13,320 --> 00:07:16,160
Isn't it just 'we will not attack unless we are attacked'?

116
00:07:16,160 --> 00:07:17,240
They both sound right.

117
00:07:17,240 --> 00:07:19,640
My teacher also asked me to emphasize this sentence

118
00:07:19,640 --> 00:07:20,960
as a motto.

119
00:07:21,600 --> 00:07:24,160
He also jokingly called it the 3L maxim.

120
00:07:25,040 --> 00:07:26,000
Indeed.

121
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:29,130
These sentences reveal the bottom line of human nature.

122
00:07:29,320 --> 00:07:31,050
Having such good faith in heart

123
00:07:31,080 --> 00:07:32,840
is benevolence and righteousness.

124
00:07:32,840 --> 00:07:35,770
Putting good faith into practice is a righteous act.

125
00:07:36,280 --> 00:07:38,409
Benevolent heart and righteous acts.

126
00:07:38,520 --> 00:07:40,480
Isn't this the right path?

127
00:07:41,840 --> 00:07:44,280
The right path is justice,

128
00:07:45,120 --> 00:07:46,240
progress,

129
00:07:46,240 --> 00:07:47,200
and light.

130
00:07:48,040 --> 00:07:48,970
On the contrary,

131
00:07:49,600 --> 00:07:50,680
it's evil,

132
00:07:51,360 --> 00:07:52,560
reactionary,

133
00:07:52,560 --> 00:07:53,560
and dark.

134
00:07:54,240 --> 00:07:55,040
That's right.

135
00:07:55,360 --> 00:07:56,159
Justice.

136
00:07:56,400 --> 00:07:57,840
What I want to say most is justice.

137
00:07:57,840 --> 00:08:01,040
I want to join the Nanyang Chinese mechanics,

138
00:08:01,040 --> 00:08:04,080
fight against the evil Japanese militarism,

139
00:08:04,080 --> 00:08:05,360
and fight for justice.

140
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:06,960
So,

141
00:08:06,960 --> 00:08:11,160
you are an international friend supporting China's anti-aggression war.

142
00:08:11,160 --> 00:08:12,240
This is

143
00:08:12,240 --> 00:08:16,300
a just cause enjoys abundant support while an unjust cause finds little.

144
00:08:21,160 --> 00:08:23,280
David is loyal and manly enough.

145
00:08:23,800 --> 00:08:25,060
Fighting for justice.

146
00:08:26,560 --> 00:08:29,480
What do you think those invaders thought back then?

147
00:08:29,480 --> 00:08:31,160
Where did they get the confidence?

148
00:08:31,160 --> 00:08:33,820
Even international friends couldn't stand it.

149
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:37,059
They actually used their crimes as capital to show off.

150
00:08:38,400 --> 00:08:39,400
These robbers.

151
00:08:39,679 --> 00:08:41,559
They knew it was burning, killing, and looting,

152
00:08:41,559 --> 00:08:43,220
but they still tried to argue.

153
00:08:43,360 --> 00:08:44,760
They not only did it openly,

154
00:08:44,760 --> 00:08:46,200
but also tried to beautify their crimes,

155
00:08:46,200 --> 00:08:47,360
and protect their identity.

156
00:08:47,360 --> 00:08:48,120
Bah.

157
00:08:48,920 --> 00:08:51,040
This is simply shameless.

158
00:08:53,520 --> 00:08:55,160
Their hearts are completely blackened.

159
00:08:55,160 --> 00:08:55,880
As for face,

160
00:08:55,880 --> 00:08:57,880
naturally they don't care about it.

161
00:08:57,880 --> 00:08:59,140
Without a conscience,

162
00:08:59,440 --> 00:09:01,240
they don't care about anything.

163
00:09:02,040 --> 00:09:02,840
However,

164
00:09:03,200 --> 00:09:05,440
there are still more good people in this world.

165
00:09:05,440 --> 00:09:08,880
So final victory will definitely stand with justice.

166
00:09:10,120 --> 00:09:11,000
Justice.

167
00:09:13,280 --> 00:09:14,810
This reminds me of a saying:

168
00:09:15,680 --> 00:09:18,480
'Justice may be late, but it will never be absent.'

169
00:09:19,240 --> 00:09:20,360
But tell me,

170
00:09:21,080 --> 00:09:23,240
why is justice always late?

171
00:09:25,720 --> 00:09:27,040
Is it possible that

172
00:09:27,040 --> 00:09:28,640
justice is always on the way,

173
00:09:28,680 --> 00:09:30,240
but it just has too much to do,

174
00:09:30,240 --> 00:09:31,440
so it's a little late?

175
00:09:32,080 --> 00:09:34,210
You've even learned to catch the joke.

176
00:09:36,040 --> 00:09:38,640
David almost couldn't come to China back then.

177
00:09:40,320 --> 00:09:42,920
Wouldn't that be a last-minute change of mind?

178
00:09:44,240 --> 00:09:46,280
He wasn't just all talk, was he?

179
00:09:47,080 --> 00:09:47,880
No.

180
00:09:48,360 --> 00:09:50,360
Because he didn't have overseas Chinese status,

181
00:09:50,360 --> 00:09:52,420
he was rejected outright at the time.

182
00:09:52,880 --> 00:09:54,240
Then isn't that smuggling?

183
00:09:54,240 --> 00:09:55,200
Smuggling?

184
00:09:55,200 --> 00:09:57,000
We came back openly and legally.

185
00:09:58,040 --> 00:10:01,000
Later, he applied to Chen Jiageng through the Taiping Relief Committee

186
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:03,520
to let him return to China for this transport mission.

187
00:10:03,520 --> 00:10:04,320
Chen Jiageng?

188
00:10:05,960 --> 00:10:08,520
Chen Jiageng specially called the Nanjing Government

189
00:10:08,520 --> 00:10:10,720
and the Southwest Transport Office responsible for the mechanics.

190
00:10:10,720 --> 00:10:13,650
In the end, they made an exception and admitted them.

191
00:10:14,200 --> 00:10:16,730
I didn't expect Chen Jiageng to be so capable.

192
00:10:17,040 --> 00:10:17,840
Capable?

193
00:10:18,440 --> 00:10:19,240
Yes!

194
00:10:19,320 --> 00:10:21,480
How else could he have founded so many schools?

195
00:10:21,480 --> 00:10:24,160
How could a single telegram solve all the problems?

196
00:10:24,160 --> 00:10:25,560
Founded so many schools?

197
00:10:26,040 --> 00:10:26,840
How many?

198
00:10:27,080 --> 00:10:28,680
You didn't know this, right?

199
00:10:28,720 --> 00:10:31,920
There are over 120 schools on record to this day.

200
00:10:32,280 --> 00:10:33,360
Over 120 schools?

201
00:10:34,320 --> 00:10:34,960
Exactly.

202
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:36,120
In my opinion,

203
00:10:36,120 --> 00:10:37,840
he was an absolute school-building fanatic.

204
00:10:37,840 --> 00:10:41,400
Though I'm curious where he got the money to build so many schools.

205
00:10:41,400 --> 00:10:45,000
Later I learned the story of him sacrificing his family wealth to build schools.

206
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:46,480
He was a real man.

207
00:10:48,480 --> 00:10:51,480
The school in front of you was founded by Chen Jiageng.

208
00:10:53,720 --> 00:10:55,280
It looks so magnificent.

209
00:10:57,080 --> 00:10:58,160
So it's no wonder

210
00:10:58,160 --> 00:11:01,880
why everyone elected Chen Jiageng as the chairman of the Nanyang Relief General Association.

211
00:11:01,880 --> 00:11:02,810
You should know,

212
00:11:02,920 --> 00:11:06,560
Wang Jingwei tried to whitewash the Japanese invaders in Southeast Asia back then.

213
00:11:06,560 --> 00:11:09,040
He called the war of aggression the 'Pan-Asianism' theory,

214
00:11:09,040 --> 00:11:11,720
and tried to undermine the ideological understanding of the public,

215
00:11:11,720 --> 00:11:13,680
attempting some sort of cultural brainwashing.

216
00:11:13,680 --> 00:11:16,080
He even wanted to sever the cultural memory of the Chinese.

217
00:11:16,080 --> 00:11:18,940
Wasn't that trying to be both a traitor and a martyr?

218
00:11:19,520 --> 00:11:23,320
However, his tricks did not blind the overseas Chinese at that time.

219
00:11:23,720 --> 00:11:26,200
In response to Wang Jingwei's surrender activities to Japan,

220
00:11:26,200 --> 00:11:30,640
Chen Jiageng angrily rebuked him: 'Before the enemy leaves our territory, anyone who speaks of peace is a traitor!'

221
00:11:30,640 --> 00:11:34,760
So under Chen Jiageng's call, everyone united,

222
00:11:34,760 --> 00:11:36,880
to resist foreign invasion together.

223
00:11:36,880 --> 00:11:37,800
That's right.

224
00:11:37,800 --> 00:11:39,520
The masses have sharp eyes.

225
00:11:41,440 --> 00:11:43,040
At any time,

226
00:11:43,040 --> 00:11:44,970
the right thing can never be wrong.

227
00:11:57,120 --> 00:11:57,840
Let's go.

228
00:11:57,840 --> 00:11:59,900
We still have a lot of places to visit.

229
00:12:00,560 --> 00:12:01,090
Let's go.

230
00:12:11,920 --> 00:12:13,160
Just this school.

231
00:12:14,480 --> 00:12:15,440
How is it?

232
00:12:15,440 --> 00:12:17,000
Does it look like Nanyang?

233
00:12:17,280 --> 00:12:19,010
Wow, this place is really nice.

234
00:12:19,480 --> 00:12:20,480
Look over there.

235
00:12:24,840 --> 00:12:25,760
Hey, stand behind him.

236
00:12:25,760 --> 00:12:26,600
I'll take a picture for both of you.
